European inflation has slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the sharp growth in the price of food products.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, recording - after 2.6 percent of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only likely 3 percent - Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the US, British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decrease, together with rising prices of raw materials and the reduction of forced unemployment, would lead to a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to an analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: "need to negotiate" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene later on this issue.
Inflation of 3.3 per cent, registered in Germany, struck the record of twelve years; while in Spain it increased from 3.6 to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation was fired in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Prices at the end of wheat increased by 88 per cent, and soy levies also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market increased this year by 52 percent, already reaching last month the black gold almost 100 dollars per barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will rise from 2.1 per cent to 2.5 per cent, but by 2009 it will decrease to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain in the next 3 or 4 months around 3 percent, however the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during 2008.
