However, we have information that domestic sales volumes are lower, many multinationals complain to survey institutes because incomes are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in the case of household appliances.
Many hospitals save themselves with disinfectants
This year, thousands of infections caused primarily by improper application of antibiotics have been recorded in hospitals.
The circumstances of hygiene prevailing in hospitals, the overcrowding of beds and the overload of the staff do not favor the control of infections - says the doctor-head department of the National Epidemiology Center.
In many hospitals it saves even the disinfectants.
Not long ago, an infection with MRSA has been diagnosed in the trauma department of the János Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital at the beginning of the year.
A seriously injured car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after returned to the hospital as a result of the infection with MRSA and since then no major surgical intervention has been possible due to the presence of the bacterium in his body.
Until December 10, this year, the National System Nosocomialis Surveillance 1094 cases of hospital infection produced by multi-resistant agents have been recorded - said Karolina Böröcz, a doctor-head of department of the National Center of Epidemiology.
This means that this number of infections produced by multi-resistant agents has certainly been recorded in hospitals, and no information is available.
Nearly two thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacilin.
One third of humans carry the bacterium of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections produced by the SA (e.g. inflammation of the throat, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once antibiotics are exaggerated or improperly applied, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, become bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and rapidly contaminate in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or sepsis in the first place in patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, in patients with the weakened organism, in the elderly, or in people with low weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the János Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, the MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Antibiotic resistant
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff cares for them in rubber and mask gloves and there are the antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are previously examined to verify the presence of MRSA in their body, but infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable taking samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections of MRSA in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Because this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and homes of the elderly, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate the patients who carry MRSA.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also because the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most cases come to public light when MRSA infections visible in the patient are already occurring - said the doctor-head department of the epidemiological center.
The European Union commits rigorously to the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological tables.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is directed, that is, microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent resistance to medications, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples is even less frequent in patients travelling or in basic care - Karolina Böröcz said.
Saves with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is contaminated with one patient to another through healthcare staff.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but there are also considerable faults in hospitals in this regard.
MRSA is infected by the transmission of drops and direct contact between people, however in the national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least for a distance of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately you can also experience - Karolina Böröcz added - that in hospitals with less favorable economic situation saves the disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a higher likelihood for infection.
In the view of Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate preventive measures are met, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the disease of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government programme against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Sickness Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is being fought against it.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, infections with MRSA show a tendency to decrease in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
