EUR 400 million more for infrastructure
Hungarian finance minister János Veres and vice-president of the European Investment Bank (EIB) Marta Gajecka signed on Friday in Budapest three credit limit agreements totalling EUR 400 million to finance education, transport and environment infrastructure, as well as the energy sector.
The European Investment Bank (EIB) approved in 2006 a budget of EUR 300 million to finance in the Hungarian budget for transport and environmental protection projects, to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund grant, of which the parties had previously signed a credit contract worth EUR 100 million, the contract they had just signed relates to the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit contract is also intended to finance the budget for educational projects.
The EIB approved a total of EUR 300 million for this Hungary objective, on the use of the remaining EUR 150 million, the decision will be taken later, by extending the credit contract.
The parties signed a contract of €50 million for innovations, which the budget will mainly use for the project of innovations and research at the University of Debrecen.
During the talks they also covered the subject of the construction of the 4th Metro line.
It was agreed that by the time Hungary completes with the EU the details of the funding of the Metro, they will again deal with the issue of whether or not the original contract needs to be modified and how to do so.
According to János Veres, this may take place earlier in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has financed a total of 113 projects in Hungary worth EUR 8.4 billion.
The interest of the credits is in line with the EURIBOR and the EIB offers a grace period of 8 years, without charging a commission to keep the loan available to the debtor.
