Fodor and six percent Hungarians
According to Environment and Hydrology Minister Gábor Fodor, expert-level meetings will end on Tuesday and Wednesday after the official inauguration will continue negotiations at the level of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world deliberate on the Bali Road Map available on post-emission reduction efforts, as set out in the Kyoto Protocol, in force until 2012.
There are currently lively discussions on the issue between developing and industrialized countries.
The United States has already indicated that it does not want to negotiate on precise figures at the moment, although it tends to agree that compared to the 1990 situation, by 2020, the emission of greenhouse gases will decrease by 25 to 40 per cent.
Another major issue of the conference is that if the industrialized countries, in addition to reducing emissions, are willing or unwilling to provide material and technological assistance to the countries in need.
A further agreement was reached on aid to developing countries.
The support fund, provided for in the Kyoto Protocol, will be led by a 16-member steering board, probably within the UN Global Environment Fund (GEF) - writes the "Piac es Profit".
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, the Minister for Environment and Hydrology Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection and to promote the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent to the 1990 level by 2020 regardless of whether or not the "post-2012 agreement" will be signed and is willing to commit itself to reducing even 30 per cent if the other major developed regions of the world and developing countries are also willing to make commitments in line with their responsibility and capacities.
Gábor Fodor pointed out that the countries that were signatories to the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 committed themselves to decline by 5.2 per cent, including the then 15 EU Member States committed themselves to achieving 8 per cent decrease.
Hungary's commitment is to reduce the greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent over the period 1985-87, which our country will comply with, says the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
It is a lot that is at stake in Bali, since in two years' time the international climate policy agreement will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed to after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments under the Kyoto Protocol would not be followed immediately by a new international emissions reduction system, the need of which was warned in its most recent report by the IPCC, an international scientific association of the United Nations dealing with climate change, which won the Nobel Peace Prize.
Thus, emission reduction would be delayed and an increase of more than 2o C in the average Earth temperature could not be prevented, which according to scientists would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British army recruits on YouTube
British military units in a video distributor publish recordings of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) was the one that took advantage of YouTube's services: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are loading videos about their actions against the Taliban - the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in the general corps of operations of Kandahar, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are now 139 recordings from Air Force soldiers that have been uploaded in this way to the Internet and their "channel" has already been seen by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "headquarter defence" and publishes videos of both actions in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Community of British Nations (Commonwealth Office) and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own YouTube channel.
Operation in Afghanistan
Originally the air force had loaded the videos with recruitment goals, but in the opinion of the Ministry of Defence they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the presence of the British army abroad.
This kind of propaganda practically costs nothing compared to conventional TV recruiting spots - the BBC said the defense expert Gordon Mackenzie - instead inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans prepared a video game
The army is also concerned that, in addition to the reciprocatingly edited and censored recordings, amateur videos appear in the distributor, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers speak at most of the losses, without yet presenting the bloody part of the fighting.
In addition, numerous videos recorded in real operations have already been uploaded from the battlefields in Iraq and Afghanistan, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different form for recruiting with free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can stand directly instead of the soldiers.
