A Heavy Memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which describe the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million files, stored over 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were not so far accessible only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an old victim or of his right people.
The eleven states in charge of their management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to the searchers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, openness has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searching "in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced workers ", explains Reto Meistern, the director of these archives administered by the International Commission of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, a number of States, such as Germany, opposed the opening of these documents to the public because of the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or the mental hangicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or the arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the peasants deported or subjected to compulsory work and, if necessary, to provide proof of their detention, in order to open the way to compensation.
Still in Bad Arolsen today, more than 300 permanent wage earners deal with tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, Director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
