Congress approves the transposition of Mifid, which entered into force on 1 November
In parallel to its parliamentary procedure, which ended today with the Congress's vote on the amendments incorporated into the bill in the Senate, the Government has submitted to the public hearing the regulations that will develop the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by Members of Parliament and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulation in order to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activities of the entities for the efficient functioning of the markets.
Mifid, which amends the Securities Market Act, involves the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improves the supervisory powers of the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and fosters cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new legislation will provide financial advisory services to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and create a new type of financial service firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFIs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are joined by multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current stock exchange managers.
The Act also obliges investment service companies to disclose on the market information on the key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and risk management forms and requires them to keep a record of all operations they carry out, in order to facilitate supervision by the CMVC.
In their passage through the Congressional Economics Commission, several changes were incorporated, among which it stresses that the entitled debts are considered a "complex" financial instrument given their high danger to the investor, which has been demonstrated with the debt of U.S. high-risk mortgages (subprime).
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that can be performed by graduates in economics and business 30 years after the actual decree delimiting professional functions reserved for economists was adopted in 1977.
