Venus: twin brother of the earth.
Despite its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the planet most similar to Earth, something that has not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlwinds in the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers have been suspected that lightning might exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves on the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent at a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous model of Urey-Miller's origin of life, lightning caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, for their part, would have given rise to amino acids that are the basic components of life.
In Venus it is not like this: if there was a life there one day, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution," says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
Today, on the surface of Venus there can be no life: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and on the surface there are temperatures of 500°C, oscillating in such a way that temperatures under zero can be reached.
"Perhaps Venus is a "diabolic" twin on Earth, but it's still a twin," Russell said.
The main objective of the "Venus Express" mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth for its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
As since the 1990s there were no special missions, just for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest results of the research that will be presented in many articles of "Nature", according to the opinion of the researchers, not only underline the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
"This also shows that neighboring planets have more common features with the Earth we had assumed," ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds in the North Pole, researchers discovered in the south polar region also a vortex formed by the clouds that rotates faster.
This phenomenon reminds the wind flows in the high terrestrial atmospheric layers of the poles, as described by a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet of the Solar System has the mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost so large.
This planet also called dawn star or evening star orbits around the Sun almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars is not much like Earth, scientists are based on the fact that both planets have been formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets water had been agglomerated that remained on Earth in the oceans, but on Venus disbanded in the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, Venus forms most of the atmosphere.
